Author-Name:    Nickell, Stephen J
Title:   Competition and Corporate Performance. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 724-46
Issue: 4
Volume: 104
Year: 1996
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  Are people right to think that competition improves corporate
 performance? The author's investigations indicate first that there are
 some theoretical reasons for believing this hypothesis to be correct but
 they are not overwhelming. Furthermore, the existing empirical evidence on
 this question is weak. However, the results reported here, based on the
 analysis of around 670 U.K. companies, provide some support for this view.
 Most important, the author presents evidence that competition, as measured
 by increased numbers of competitors or by lower levels of rents, is
 associated with a significantly higher rate of total factor productivity
 growth.  Copyright 1996 by University of Chicago Press.
